On Escalation Ticket # 00416192 the new comment has been added: Augustina Sidor:

The query provided is a workaround to fix the 'license' column state from the Computers page.

This status is set by a flag (trialversion from clientmachine table.). If its value is NULL or lower than 1, the status for the machine will be set as "Unlicensed", otherwise the status will be "Licensed".

The query will set the flag as null for the machines that don't have a license associated.

One of the situations when the value of this flag is changed is when the Automatic Release License is set.

To investigate what went wrong, please provide us the following information:

	 - 	When the automatic license released was set to run?
	 - 	Please check how many machines are in this situation.


	 - 	SELECT COUNT(1) FROM clientmachine WHERE reregister=1 AND trialversion IS NOT NULL;
	 - 	Check the value of trialversion  and when the machine has communicated last time 

	 - 	SELECT id, name, lastseen, trialversion FROM clientmachine WHERE reregister=1 AND trialversion IS NOT NULL;

[DevOps CommentId:10647232]

Hi!
The screenshots were attached to the ticket.
As you can see in the screenshots, we have computers which checked with the server 91 days ago, and which still appear as licensed. I can confirm that they do not have a license assigned, but the fact that they appear as license will mess with the reports the customers have to export.

Please let me know which is the next step for this investigation.

Is there something we can do in a future server update which will address this?
As the customers do not want to apply workarounds, like the command to update the license column in the computers table.

Thank you,

On Escalation Ticket # 00416192 the new comment has been added: Augustina Sidor:

Kindly inform the customer that implementing the provided workaround is the only solution to resolve the issue with the 'License' state column from the Computers page.


To obtain more information on why the column is not being upgraded properly, please enable the log for the cron job that manages the automatic license release.
>> touch /var/eppfiles/automatic_release_license.log

You may keep the log enabled for one day, but please avoid extending it beyond that as it may impact server performance.

After one day, kindly retrieve the file's content from the server and then delete the file.
>> rm /var/eppfiles/automatic_release_license.log






FYI @WaitingOnEngineer
